promoted.

25:57.278 --> 26:02.846
So I started off working in the chemicals area 
because I was working on a butadiene unit and a

25:57.278 --> 26:02.846
butyl plant. We had just acquired the butadiene 
and the butyl plant from the federal government in

26:04.168 --> 26:11.518
March of 1955, right before I showed up. And at that 
point in time, we were dehydrogenated normal

26:14.198 --> 26:21.368
butylenes. We had a process where we took the C4 
strain, we used acid extraction to get

26:21.608 --> 26:28.477
isobutylene, and that went to the butyl rubber 
plane. We had an

26:29.418 --> 26:37.489
extractive distillation process where we 
separated the butylenes from the butanes, okay?

26:42.650 --> 26:47.055
It was, we called it the GK unit, I don't know. It was 
a, I forgot what kind of extractive or azeotropic

26:47.075 --> 26:57.728
type, just a what?

26:57.748 --> 27:06.919
And then we take the butylenes and dehydrogenate 
them, you know, over the old shell 105 catalyst,

26:57.748 --> 27:06.919
which is an iron oxide, I think. and using very high 
temperature steam, 1400 degrees or something

27:07.912 --> 27:18.245
like that. I remember that it was anytime you heard 
that there was a steam leak at the dehydro unit, you

27:18.265 --> 27:25.955
didn't walk. What you did is you got a pole and put a 
rag on the end of it because you cannot see 1400

27:26.556 --> 27:34.105
degree steam. And therefore, when the little 
handkerchief disappeared, you knew where the

27:34.372 --> 27:39.817
leak was.

27:42.720 --> 27:49.587
